5 Keys building a community - I did it In NYC , so can you (I invite you to figure out your why and figure out your business mission statement/core values) super important 

1. The art of SHOWING up 
/but also the magic of showing up on time. So what if “NY” has a vibe of everything starts 10-15mins late…. Don’t fall into the trap of how everyone is ok with being a little late. The way your students start showing up on time is if YOU DO. 

2. Shooting your classes from the hip won’t keep them coming. Working on a curriculum that is flexible is key. 

3. Work on yourself, more in depth than just “dancing”. Stop putting yourself on a high horse/pedestal. You’re not better than your students. 

4. Just because you can dance and move, ….. that won’t keep your students coming. Definitely look into Stepping outside of the box from dance “skills” at times and show them skills of life.

5. Don’t give up just because your first class only 3 students showed up. It’s important to Make sure you pour your heart in all of the classes wether is 1-50 students. the compound effect will be in your favor if you become passionate about the Core Values of what you’re doing.

Traditional, Dominican Bachata (aka Bachata 😉) has snuck up on me, I can’t lie- I learned to dance in the Bay Area, where I had more exposure to artists like Juan Liuis Guerra, Prince Royce and maybe Romeo Santos. It’s nice for a social, but I definitely didn’t enjoy it as much as salsa (and some leads took bachata as an invite to dance much more closely than I was interested in, or initiate touch that felt incomfortable without asking).

It took several years before I met Dominican friends who introduced me to amazing bachata artists loke Joe Veras, Luis Vargas, Raulin Rodriguez, Leonardo Paniagua and to reslly start to understand how rich bachata is as a musical genre- it SLAPS, y’all! That requinto and güira is everything. 

Then it took meeting @acefusion_official, the first non-binary instructor I have known in the Afro-Latin Dance scene, to realize that Traditional Bachata was also one of the most fun, accessible ways for me to learn to lead and feel affirmed as a queer dancer. 

I am so thrilled Ace has been here offering classes in New York because I’ve realized Traditional Bachata gives me so much LIFE! And last night was such good practice in letting myself live in the movement and enjoy it.

✨3 reasons why Bachata Traditional is my favorite music genre to dance✨

This dance sums up why I love this style the most.

✅ Simple yet groovy music which allows maximum freedom of expression for leads and follows. 

Notice us interpret music on our own terms yet staying connected through the whole dance by a common timing. I believe that simplicity, freedom of self-expression and good connection(to self, partner and music) are the secret ingredients to a fun dance, so this style resonates with me the most. Not to mention the vocals that add a deep impact to the way it makes me feel!

✅ No turn patterns needed to enjoy this music.

Notice us grooving to the song by just dancing out basics in place without a single turn pattern. You don’t always need thousands layers of turns or complexity to enjoy dancing to this music! 

 ✅ No gender roles on who should lead or follow.

Notice us switch between leading and follow through the dance. Coming from a lead’s perspective, I don’t prefer when someone turns me too much or tries sensual stuff when I follow. This is the only style where I can enjoy following without having to do the things I mentioned. I love following once in a while because it helps me tap into a flow state of letting go of control and enjoy the moment with the lead!

What is your favorite thing about Bachata?❤️

Love dancing with my sensei @acefusion_official ❤️

Question that’s been asked lately - where is bachata going ? 

Bachata’s future is so bright. More and more instructors/competitors are getting curious on how the culture feels/expresses bachata. Meaning the truth will continue to surface on the beautiful bachata cultural dance.

The truth that is does not need to be overly sexualize to enjoy/fused up to make it cool “marketable”

The truth that dancing on 1 is the Studio (studied way). 
The truth that there are possibilities of feeling bachata on 2, 3, and 4. 

The truth that the music is not evolving if it’s taking away its components.

The truth that it’s ok to dance bachata in whatever style you love… however the roots alone are good enough and saucy enough to carry it first true name “Bachata” no matter the style of “bachata style” you prefer…. Truth is if you cannot for one bit connect with dancers from the culture or not an even a bit curious about Bachata in its birth place….do you truly understand/respect/honor the culture ???? 

So much in my heart…. Cheers to 2024 where dancers get even more curious about the roots before the “fusion” 

“Roots before fusion” 

Dear educators of the dance community, let’s continue to Spread the truth and the roots !!!!! May our students fall in love with Dominican Republic 🇩🇴 dancers / bachata history and the culture 🫡🫡🫡 and may many more students fall in love with NOT sexualizing a partner work dance…….
